# GOV-001: Settlement at scale — re-litigation, multi-root stores, keys

**Status:** REVIEW GATE CLOSED, rev 4 (2026-07-07) — three model families reviewed, the third verdict was *amend-then-adopt* and rev 4 integrates every amendment; ready for SPEC v0.3 drafting + the implementation gate
**Origin:** Kimi k2.6 governance audit of the sigma-glyph warrant store (issues [#5](https://github.com/s0fractal/warrant/issues/5), [#6](https://github.com/s0fractal/warrant/issues/6), [#7](https://github.com/s0fractal/warrant/issues/7)) + Opus 4.8 review F3 (binding).
**Gate reviews:** 2 — each forced a revision, and the second broke part of the first's fix; the gate is working.
- Codex on rev 1 (`reviews/2026-07-codex-gov001-gate.md`): *revise* — all three of rev 1's attack-asks broke (byte-novelty probe; mass-adoption; both-keys rotation refuted as protection — a false claim in rev 1's own rationale).
- Gemini 3.1 Pro on rev 2 (`reviews/2026-07-gemini-gov001-gate.md`): *revise* — Codex's "explicitly names the settled claim" is **unimplementable** against the v0.2 schema (unknown fields in a check reason are fatal; probe reproduced by the maintainer); the rev 2 key-conflict freeze hands an attacker a perpetual veto over rotation; `genesis.json` needed for portable jurisdiction.
- DeepSeek v4 Pro on rev 3 (`reviews/2026-07-deepseek-gov001-gate.md`): ***amend-then-adopt*** — the stale-rotation replay attack on conflicted-key exclusion **fails** (DAG ordering: a stale rotation is an ancestor, never a conflict — state machine walked explicitly); strawman flooding is acceptable separation of concerns; fingerprints are computable from v0.2 records with no schema change. One P1: `genesis.json` must be advisory, never a trust anchor. Six P2 tightenings. All integrated in rev 4.

## Design stance

One principle resolves most of the open questions: **in this format, an
argument is admissible when it is executable.** Prose persuades; checks
settle. v0.2 already lives by this for decisions (`ski@v1`, filing-time
re-runs); v0.3 extends it to the *governance* of decisions. The gate
added two corollaries: every rule must be **mechanically decidable**
(novelty by outcome fingerprint, root authority by explicit activation,
key state by DAG order — Codex), and the format may only decide what it
can represent: **novelty is format, relevance is policy** (Gemini).

## 1. Re-litigation standard (SPEC §7 replacement) — closes #5

Failure modes at scale (Kimi): evidence foreclosure by volume;
interpretation lock-in. Precedent: sigma-glyph ADR-004 re-opened a
settled point citing the already-shipped artifact.

**Candidate §7 text (rev 3):**

> **Tunnel.** A settling warrant's tunnel has a record set and a blob
> set. The record set is the transitive closure of `prior` edges through
> stored warrants. The blob set is the union of `under`, `evidence`,
> `subject.hash`, `check`, and `transcript` hashes cited by those
> records. Verifiers MUST NOT recursively parse arbitrary blobs for
> additional tunnel links unless a runtime-specific rule explicitly says
> so. A blob hash that is also the WarrantID of a stored record is still
> a blob reference unless it appears in `prior` or in a field whose rule
> explicitly names WarrantIDs.
>
> **Foreclosure.** A blob forecloses only the claims that some reason in
> the tunnel actually makes about it: mere presence in an `evidence`
> array forecloses nothing.
>
> **Re-litigation.** A re-litigation warrant MUST carry at least one of:
> (a) an evidence hash absent from the tunnel's blob set, or
> (b) a **new demonstrable consequence** of evidence already present:
> a check, all of whose blobs are resolvable, that re-runs to a
> previously absent **outcome fingerprint** within the settling tunnel.
>
> Outcome fingerprints: for `ski@v1` —
> `{runtime, term, expect, verdict, result_node_hash}`; for `cmd@v1` —
> `{runtime, sorted evidence hashes, verdict, transcript hash}`, and
> `transcript` is REQUIRED for §7(b) use. A check whose outcome
> fingerprint already appears in the tunnel is not new, even if the
> check blob hash differs. Prose MAY explain why the consequence
> matters, but prose is not part of the novelty test and alone never
> re-opens settlement.
>
> For determining whether an outcome fingerprint appears in the tunnel,
> only check reasons that supply all required fields (including
> `transcript` for `cmd@v1`) are considered: a tunnel reason lacking a
> required field is not part of the tunnel's fingerprint set and cannot
> block novelty under (b). (The `evidence` array is not ordered by JCS;
> the fingerprint sorts the hex hashes ascending lexicographically.)
>
> **Novelty ≠ relevance.** The format layer decides only whether an
> outcome is new; whether a novel check is *relevant* to the settled
> subject — or a strawman testing something adjacent — MUST be decided
> by the active settlement policy, not the core format. (The v0.2
> check-reason schema is closed: unknown fields are fatal, so a check
> cannot "name" a claim in-band, and the format cannot know what
> semantic claim a blob tests. Gemini gate review, probe verified.)
>
> Tools SHOULD refuse to file re-litigation warrants that carry neither
> (a) nor (b); verifiers SHOULD flag them
> `WARN: re-litigation cites nothing new`.
>
> NOTE: because novelty is purely syntactic, a permissive-policy store
> may accumulate unbounded fingerprint-distinct but substantively
> irrelevant re-litigations. Implementations SHOULD provide configurable
> limits (e.g. re-litigations per tunnel); such limits are policy
> choices, not format requirements.

This admits the ADR-004 precedent (a new executable witness over the
already-shipped artifact) and rejects cosmetic restatements — same
verdict, same observable outcome, different bytes — mechanically.

Meta-rule (Kimi's ossification point): §7 itself is challengeable under
(b) — a check demonstrating that the rule forces a wrong settlement is
admissible evidence against the rule. Constitutions that can only be
amended from outside die outside; this one accepts executable
amendments.

## 2. Multi-root stores (new SPEC §9) — closes #6

The sigma-glyph store is already a two-root DAG. Rev 1 conflated two
things the gate separated: *who filed a root* vs *whether it settles
anything*.

**Candidate §9 text (rev 3):**

> A store is a DAG. A **root** is a record with empty `prior`.
>
> - A root is **well-signed** if its filing signature is valid and (with
>   a keyring configured) bound.
> - A root is **settlement-active** only if either:
>   1. it is listed in the verifier's local trust configuration as a
>      genesis root for this store; or
>   2. it is adopted by a settlement-active root through an `accept`
>      warrant whose `subject.hash` is the WarrantID of the root to be
>      adopted, and whose signatures satisfy the adopting root's current
>      settlement policy, including any threshold rule.
>
> Verifiers MAY verify inactive roots for local integrity, but MUST
> exclude inactive/unadopted roots from settlement and foreclosure
> calculations and MUST report `WARN: unadopted root`.
>
> **Adoption is scoped:** adopting root A makes root B settlement-active
> for A's jurisdiction; it does not make B globally authoritative for
> unrelated roots. Two roots that never reference each other are
> separate jurisdictions sharing a blob store — by design.
>
> **Portable jurisdiction:** stores SHOULD contain `genesis.json` in the
> store root — JCS-canonical `{"roots": ["<WarrantID>", ...]}`. The file
> is **advisory**; verifiers MUST NOT treat it as a trust anchor — it is
> mutable, unsigned, and editable by anyone with store write access.
> Before using its listed roots as settlement-active, a verifier MUST
> independently verify its authenticity (typically by pinning its
> expected hash in local trust configuration, or by explicit user
> acceptance). If `genesis.json` is present but unverified, the verifier
> MUST report `WARN: genesis.json unverified` and MUST NOT use its
> contents for settlement. (DeepSeek gate 3, P1.)
>
> **Missing blobs, split by function:** for *settlement*, a record with
> unresolvable settlement-critical references is settlement-inactive
> until they resolve (status-quo caution — it settles nothing new); this
> does not change its WarrantID or base verification result, and
> unresolved references in v0.1/v0.2 records remain the §6 warnings they
> are today. For *foreclosure*, an unresolvable blob forecloses nothing
> (challenger fairness — what cannot be read cannot have been reasoned
> over).

## 3. Keys: binding, rotation, thresholds (SPEC §5 v0.3) — closes #7

v0.2 has one Ed25519 key and no keyring; F3 (Opus) added the honest
`binding unverified (no keyring)` warning. Rev 1's both-keys rotation
rule was refuted at the gate: under outgoing-key compromise the attacker
generates the incoming key too, so an outgoing+incoming pair is not
evidence of legitimate rotation.

**Candidate §5 additions (rev 3):**

> Key state derives from key-state warrants — **any cache is an
> implementation detail, the warrants are the truth.** Implementations
> MAY derive an internal key-state cache; any such cache MUST be purely
> deterministic from the DAG of key-state warrants; no interchangeable
> `keyring.json` format is mandated by this spec. With key state
> configured (genesis keys pinned in local trust configuration plus
> derived rotations), verifiers MUST report each signature as `bound` or
> `unbound`; without it, the v0.2 warning stands. Bound/unbound is a
> report unless a v0.3 policy explicitly makes bound signatures required
> for settlement-grade verification.
>
> **Rotation is a warrant:** an `accept` whose subject is the new key
> blob. A rotation MUST include a valid signature by the incoming key as
> proof of possession and MUST be authorized under the actor/store's
> current key policy. If that policy has a threshold, the rotation MUST
> satisfy it using keys that were already bound before the rotation; the
> incoming key's proof-of-possession signature does not count toward the
> threshold. The outgoing key's signature MAY be required by policy for
> ordinary rotation, but MUST NOT be sufficient authorization when the
> store has a multi-actor threshold policy. Emergency replacement of a
> suspected-compromised outgoing key SHOULD be authorized by quorum
> without requiring the outgoing key.
>
> **Revocation is a warrant:** a `supersede` of the rotation warrant
> that introduced the key, authorized under the same current-policy
> rule.
>
> **Ordering:** key validity windows derive from accepted
> rotation/revocation warrants in **DAG order**, not from
> unauthenticated wall-clock trust in `ts` alone. A `ts` outside the
> non-decreasing prior order remains a §6 warning and MUST NOT by itself
> extend or resurrect a key.
>
> **Conflicts.** Only *authorized* key-state warrants can conflict: a
> record that fails current-policy authorization is an invalid record,
> not a conflict — an attacker without quorum cannot manufacture one.
> When two authorized key-state warrants are unordered by the DAG
> (fork-and-merge), verifiers MUST report `WARN: key-state conflict`,
> and the conflicted actor's key MUST NOT count toward any quorum until
> a later warrant — authorized by the **unconflicted remainder** of the
> quorum — resolves the conflict. If the policy threshold would become
> unsatisfiable, it is reduced to exclude the conflicted actor (e.g.
> 3-of-3 → 2-of-2) strictly for the purpose of conflict resolution.
> Freezing only the *transitions* (rev 2) was rejected at the gate: it
> reverts to the prior key state, keeping a compromised key alive and
> letting its holder veto resolution forever.
>
> A key-state warrant is conflicting only if no later authorized warrant
> for the same actor is its DAG descendant: warrants ordered by the DAG
> (one reachable from the other) are never a conflict, even when they
> sit on different branches — only maximal, mutually unordered warrants
> trigger this rule. (A replayed stale rotation is an ancestor of the
> current one by construction and therefore harmless — DeepSeek gate 3,
> attack walked and refuted.)
>
> **Threshold policy grammar.** A v0.3 threshold policy blob, if
> present, MUST be JCS-canonical JSON:
>
> ```json
> {
>   "warrant_policy": "0.3",
>   "threshold": { "min_sigs": 2, "actors": ["a@x", "b@y", "c@z"] }
> }
> ```
>
> `min_sigs` MUST be a positive integer ≤ `len(actors)`; `actors` MUST
> be nonempty and unique; unknown fields inside `threshold` make the
> policy invalid. Records filed under an invalid threshold policy are
> settlement-inactive and MUST produce `ERR: invalid threshold policy`
> for settlement-grade verification. Opaque v0.1/v0.2 policy blobs MUST
> NOT be interpreted as threshold policies by accident.

Single outgoing-key compromise under these rules: the attacker can sign
as the outgoing key and can mint an incoming key, but an
outgoing+incoming pair authorizes nothing by itself — protection comes
from the current-policy quorum of already-bound keys, from excluding the
incoming key from that quorum, and from DAG-ordered key state that `ts`
games cannot resurrect. Dumped blobs still foreclose nothing per §7.

## Compatibility (rev 2 — replaces rev 1's blanket claim)

Every v0.1/v0.2 body that was schema-valid remains schema-valid under
its declared version; v0.3 settlement rules MUST NOT turn a v0.1/v0.2
record into a schema error. Unresolved references in v0.1/v0.2 records
remain §6 verification warnings; the settlement-inactive consequence
applies only to v0.3 settlement indexes. Threshold checks activate only
for blobs that declare `"warrant_policy": "0.3"`. Keyring binding status
is a report unless a v0.3 policy says otherwise. Stores without
keyrings keep today's behavior plus today's warnings.

## Review gate history

Rev 1's asks broke (Codex); rev 2's asks broke (Gemini: strawman churn
moved to the policy layer; `genesis.json` for portability; the conflict
freeze was a rotation DoS → conflicted-key exclusion). Rev 3's asks were
answered by DeepSeek (gate 3): the stale-rotation replay **fails** under
DAG ordering (attack walked and refuted; maximal-warrant clarification
added); `genesis.json` **was** a P1 trust hazard (now advisory-only);
strawman flooding is policy's problem (operational note added). Verdict:
amend-then-adopt — all amendments integrated in rev 4. **Gate closed:
three model families, each round strictly improving the text.**

